problem:
Let \[f(n) = \left\{
\begin{array}{cl}
n^3+2n-1 &\text{ if }n>1, \\
n-1 &\text{ if }n \le 1.
\end{array}
\right.\]Find $f(0)+f(1)+f(2)$.

solution:
We apply the distributive property to get\begin{align*}
\frac{1}{4}\left(\frac{4}{y}+4y\right)&= \frac{1}{4}\cdot\frac{4}{y}+\frac{1}{4}\cdot 4y\\
&= \boxed{\frac{1}{y} + y}.
\end{align*}

We can simplify directly

\begin{align*}
2\left(\frac{7!}{3!4!}\right) &= 2\left(\frac{7\cdot 6 \cdot 5}{3 \cdot 2 \cdot 1}\right) \\
&= \frac{7 \cdot 6 \cdot 5}{3 \cdot 1} \\
&= 7 \cdot 2 \cdot 5 \\
&= \boxed{70}
\end{align*}

